Vheadline
p2
VA duet to remember
p3
sVnews
p4
VAs part of its Golden Jubilee year celebrations, South Indian Cultural Association arranged a vocal duet by Hyderabad Brothers, D. Raghavachary and Seshachary, at Ravindra Bharati. Surya Deepti on violin, Kaliprasad on mridangam and Shyamkumar on kanjira accompanied them.The concert opened with aNavaragamalika Varnam Valachi Vachi. Later, they rendered a rare Manipravala kritiTarunam Idammaof Shyama Sastry . Afterwards, they presentedSabhapatikiin Abhogi andBagayenayyain Chandrajyothi; they gave a sketch of the raga Sarasangi and presented it in a rareNeekela Dayaraduof Ramaswamy Sivan, adding impressive swaraprasthara and maintaining the melodic impact.Thodi, a rich raga with no bounds for expansion, was their main stay of the concert. The brothers built-up the melody,  scanning through the threesthayis.Ninne Namminanuof Shyama Sastry in Misrachapu talam, was their number of choice in this raga. The rendition was expressive with perfect sahitya bhava. The nereval and swaram too were praise-worthy .Violinist Surya Deepti maintained the melodic line and responded well with a brief sketch of the raga . The tani avaratanam by the percussionists added to the richness of the number. Notable among other compositions  in this concert wereEnnadu Jootunoin Kalavati of Thyagaraja and a rare Tamil PadamEthanai Sonnalumof Vaidkeeswaram Koil Subbarayar. Purandaradasa&#8217;s popular numberKrishna Nee Begane Baroin Yaman Kalyan concluded the show.
